Likelihood Analysis with log transformed ratios

# Filter likelihood condition data
likelihood_data <- data %>% filter(condition == "likelihood")

# Evidence pieces
evidence_cols <- c("p1", "p2", "p3", "p4", "d1", "d2", "d3", "d4")

# Function to safely calculate log ratios (avoiding log(0))
safe_log_ratio <- function(numerator, denominator) {
  # Convert 0 to 0.1 and 100 to 99.9
  safe_denom <- ifelse(denominator <= 0, 0.1, ifelse(denominator >= 100, 99.9, denominator))
  safe_num <- ifelse(numerator <= 0, 0.1, ifelse(numerator >= 100, 99.9, numerator))
  return(log(safe_num / safe_denom))
}

# Calculate log likelihood ratios for each evidence piece
likelihood_log_results <- list()

for (evidence in evidence_cols) {
  # Get column names for this evidence
  g_col <- paste0(evidence, "_likelihood_g")
  ng_col <- paste0(evidence, "_likelihood_ng")
  
  # Calculate log ratios for each participant
  likelihood_data <- likelihood_data %>%
    mutate(!!paste0(evidence, "_log_ratio") := safe_log_ratio(!!sym(g_col), !!sym(ng_col)))
  
  # Calculate means by verdict
  means <- likelihood_data %>%
    group_by(verdict) %>%
    summarise(mean_log_ratio = mean(!!sym(paste0(evidence, "_log_ratio")), na.rm = TRUE),
              .groups = 'drop')
  
  likelihood_log_results[[evidence]] <- means
}

print("=== LIKELIHOOD LOG RATIOS ===")
## [1] "=== LIKELIHOOD LOG RATIOS ==="
for (evidence in evidence_cols) {
  means <- likelihood_log_results[[evidence]]
  guilty_mean <- means$mean_log_ratio[means$verdict == "Guilty"]
  not_guilty_mean <- means$mean_log_ratio[means$verdict == "Not Guilty"]
  
  cat(sprintf("%s: Guilty = %.4f, Not Guilty = %.4f, Difference = %.4f\n", 
              toupper(evidence), guilty_mean, not_guilty_mean, guilty_mean - not_guilty_mean))
}

Diagnostic Analysis

diagnostic_data <- data %>% filter(condition == "diagnostic")

# Calculate log diagnostic ratios: log(P(Evidence|Guilty) / P(Evidence|Not Guilty))
diagnostic_log_results <- list()

for (evidence in evidence_cols) {
  # Get column names - diagnostic uses _t (true/guilty) and _f (false/not guilty)
  t_col <- paste0(evidence, "_diagnostic_t")  # P(Evidence|Guilty)
  f_col <- paste0(evidence, "_diagnostic_f")  # P(Evidence|Not Guilty)
  
  # Calculate log ratios
  diagnostic_data <- diagnostic_data %>%
    mutate(!!paste0(evidence, "_log_diagnostic") := safe_log_ratio(!!sym(t_col), !!sym(f_col)))
  
  # Calculate means by verdict
  means <- diagnostic_data %>%
    group_by(verdict) %>%
    summarise(mean_log_diagnostic = mean(!!sym(paste0(evidence, "_log_diagnostic")), na.rm = TRUE),
              .groups = 'drop')
  
  diagnostic_log_results[[evidence]] <- means
}

print("=== DIAGNOSTIC LOG RATIOS ===")

Formal Statistics

# Likelihood log ratio ANOVA (should show minimal effects)
likelihood_log_long <- likelihood_data %>%
  select(id, verdict, ends_with("_log_ratio")) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = ends_with("_log_ratio"), 
               names_to = "evidence", 
               values_to = "log_ratio") %>%
  mutate(evidence = str_remove(evidence, "_log_ratio"))

print("=== LIKELIHOOD LOG RATIO ANOVA (Should show minimal effects) ===")
## [1] "=== LIKELIHOOD LOG RATIO ANOVA (Should show minimal effects) ==="
if (nrow(likelihood_log_long) > 0) {
  likelihood_log_aov <- aov_ez(id = "id", 
                              dv = "log_ratio", 
                              data = likelihood_log_long,
                              between = "verdict",
                              within = "evidence")
  
  print(likelihood_log_aov)
  
  # Pairwise comparisons for likelihood log ratios
  likelihood_log_emm <- emmeans(likelihood_log_aov, ~ verdict | evidence)
  likelihood_log_pairs <- pairs(likelihood_log_emm)
  print("\nLikelihood log ratio pairwise comparisons:")
  print(summary(likelihood_log_pairs))
}

Explanation of Discrepancy

OK, so this is why we have the discrepancy. Using fingerprint evidence (P1) as an example, participants who voted “guilty” rated the evidence as having a 79.4% probability of occurring if Derek was guilty and a 31.6% probability if Derek was innocent. Participants who voted “not guilty” rated the same evidence as 42.4% likely if guilty and 15.1% likely if innocent.

The subtraction method calculates the difference between these two probability ratings for each participant. Guilty voters showed a mean difference of 47.8 points (79.4 - 31.6), while not-guilty voters showed a mean difference of 27.3 points (42.4 - 15.1). The crucial finding is the between-group difference: 47.8 - 27.3 = 20.5 points. This represents a bias because it captures how differently the two groups weight evidence for guilt versus innocence. Guilty voters see evidence as much more diagnostic of guilt than innocent voters see the same evidence.

When we calculate ratios instead (79.4/31.6 = 2.51 for guilty voters versus 42.4/15.1 = 2.81 for not-guilty voters), the difference between groups becomes much smaller (2.81 - 2.51 = 0.30). This compression occurs because ratios are inherently less sensitive to absolute differences when both the numerator and denominator are in the middle-to-high range. The mathematical properties of division tend to normalize differences, especially when dealing with probability ratings that cluster away from the extreme values of 0 and 100.

Results Formal Explanation

We conducted a pilot study (N = 58) investigating confirmation bias in legal evidence evaluation using a 2 (reasoning type: likelihood vs. diagnostic) × 2 (verdict: guilty vs. not guilty) mixed design. Participants recruited via Prolific read a burglary case and made initial guilt judgments, then evaluated eight pieces of evidence using either likelihood reasoning (probability of guilt given evidence) or diagnostic reasoning (probability of evidence given guilt status). The likelihood condition included 24 participants (15 guilty, 9 not guilty verdicts), while the diagnostic condition included 34 participants (17 guilty, 17 not guilty verdicts).

We analyzed evidence ratings using two mathematical approaches: (1) log-transformed ratios, following standard Bayesian analysis procedures, and (2) raw difference scores (subtraction method). For likelihood reasoning, we calculated P(Guilty|Evidence True) - P(Guilty|Evidence False). For diagnostic reasoning, we calculated P(Evidence|Guilty) - P(Evidence|Not Guilty). Mixed-design ANOVAs tested for main effects of verdict and evidence type, with pairwise comparisons examining individual evidence items.

The key finding was that confirmation bias detection depended critically on the analytical approach used. Log-ratio analyses revealed minimal effects of verdict on evidence evaluation in both reasoning conditions (likelihood: F(1,22) = 2.28, p = .145; diagnostic: F(1,32) = 1.11, p = .299). These results suggested objective, unbiased evidence processing consistent with normative Bayesian reasoning.

However, subtraction analyses revealed substantial confirmation bias effects in both conditions. For likelihood reasoning, participants who initially judged the defendant guilty showed significantly larger difference scores than those who judged him not guilty (F(1,22) = 13.57, p = .001). For diagnostic reasoning, this bias effect was even stronger (F(1,32) = 20.01, p < .001). Pairwise comparisons showed significant verdict effects for multiple evidence types in both conditions using the subtraction method.

In the likelihood condition using subtraction analysis, significant verdict differences emerged for P2 (fingerprint evidence, p = .0036), P4 (witness testimony, p = .0103), D1 (work order evidence, p = .0090), and D4 (alibi evidence, p = .0219). In the diagnostic condition, significant effects were found for P1 (fiber evidence, p = .0282), P4 (witness testimony, p = .0044), D1 (work order evidence, p = .0057), D2 (circumstantial evidence, p = .0106), and D4 (alibi evidence, p = .0409).

The bias was substantial. For diagnostic reasoning subtraction scores, guilty voters showed mean differences ranging from 1.06 to 47.76 points, while not-guilty voters showed mean differences ranging from -36.88 to 27.35 points. The largest between-group difference was 32.24 points for work order evidence (D1), indicating that participants who initially judged guilt saw exonerating evidence as much less diagnostic than those who initially judged innocence.

Type 1 Model: Causal Power + Coherence

Function to apply diagnostic equations for Type 1 model

apply_causal_power_equations <- function(data, evidence_cols) {
  
  results_list <- list()
  
  for(evidence in evidence_cols) {
    
    cat("Processing evidence:", evidence, "\n")
    
    # Get the appropriate columns based on condition
    if("diagnostic" %in% unique(data$condition)) {
      # Diagnostic condition: P(Evidence|Guilty) and P(Evidence|Not Guilty)
      p_e_given_g_col <- paste0(evidence, "_diagnostic_t") 
      p_e_given_ng_col <- paste0(evidence, "_diagnostic_f")
      
      # Check if columns exist
      if(p_e_given_g_col %in% names(data) && p_e_given_ng_col %in% names(data)) {
        
        diagnostic_data <- data %>% 
          filter(condition == "diagnostic") %>%
          filter(!is.na(!!sym(p_e_given_g_col)) & !is.na(!!sym(p_e_given_ng_col)))
        
        if(nrow(diagnostic_data) > 0) {
          # Convert to probabilities (0-1 scale)
          diagnostic_data <- diagnostic_data %>%
            mutate(
              p_e_given_g = !!sym(p_e_given_g_col) / 100,
              p_e_given_ng = !!sym(p_e_given_ng_col) / 100
            )
          
          # Calculate DelatP (your causal power measure)
          diagnostic_data <- diagnostic_data %>%
            mutate(delta_p = p_e_given_g - p_e_given_ng)
          
          # Apply your diagnostic equations
          if(evidence %in% c("p1", "p2", "p3", "p4")) {
            # Generative evidence: P(guilty|evidence) = [DeltaP + P(evidence|innocent)] / [DeltaP + 2×P(evidence|innocent)]
            diagnostic_data <- diagnostic_data %>%
              mutate(predicted_guilt = pmax(0.01, pmin(0.99, (delta_p + p_e_given_ng) / (delta_p + 2 * p_e_given_ng))))
          } else {
            # Preventive evidence (d1-d4): P(guilty|no_evidence) = [|DeltaP| + P(no_evidence|innocent)] / [|DeltaP| + 2×P(no_evidence|innocent)]
            diagnostic_data <- diagnostic_data %>%
              mutate(
                p_no_e_given_ng = 1 - p_e_given_ng,
                predicted_guilt = pmax(0.01, pmin(0.99, (abs(delta_p) + p_no_e_given_ng) / (abs(delta_p) + 2 * p_no_e_given_ng)))
              )
          }
          
          # Convert back to 0-100 scale
          diagnostic_data <- diagnostic_data %>%
            mutate(predicted_guilt_percentage = predicted_guilt * 100)
          
          # Store results
          results_list[[paste0(evidence, "_diagnostic")]] <- diagnostic_data %>%
            select(id, verdict, delta_p, predicted_guilt, predicted_guilt_percentage, p_e_given_g, p_e_given_ng)
        }
      } else {
        cat("Warning: Columns", p_e_given_g_col, "or", p_e_given_ng_col, "not found for", evidence, "\n")
      }
    }
    
    if("likelihood" %in% unique(data$condition)) {
      # Likelihood condition: P(Guilty|Evidence True) and P(Guilty|Evidence False)
      p_g_given_e_col <- paste0(evidence, "_likelihood_g")
      p_g_given_ne_col <- paste0(evidence, "_likelihood_ng")
      
      # Check if columns exist
      if(p_g_given_e_col %in% names(data) && p_g_given_ne_col %in% names(data)) {
        
        likelihood_data <- data %>% 
          filter(condition == "likelihood") %>%
          filter(!is.na(!!sym(p_g_given_e_col)) & !is.na(!!sym(p_g_given_ne_col)))
        
        if(nrow(likelihood_data) > 0) {
          # These are already the guilt judgments we want to predict
          # We can use them to reverse-engineer the causal power parameters
          likelihood_data <- likelihood_data %>%
            mutate(
              p_g_given_e = !!sym(p_g_given_e_col) / 100,
              p_g_given_ne = !!sym(p_g_given_ne_col) / 100,
              observed_difference = p_g_given_e - p_g_given_ne
            )
          
          results_list[[paste0(evidence, "_likelihood")]] <- likelihood_data %>%
            select(id, verdict, observed_difference, p_g_given_e, p_g_given_ne)
        }
      } else {
        cat("Warning: Columns", p_g_given_e_col, "or", p_g_given_ne_col, "not found for", evidence, "\n")
      }
    }
  }
  
  return(results_list)
}

Function to test coherence effects on causal power estimates

test_coherence_on_causal_power <- function(data, evidence_cols) {
  
  coherence_results <- list()
  
  # Focus on diagnostic condition where we can measure DeltaP directly
  diagnostic_data <- data %>% filter(condition == "diagnostic")
  
  if(nrow(diagnostic_data) == 0) {
    cat("Warning: No diagnostic condition data found\n")
    return(coherence_results)
  }
  
  for(evidence in evidence_cols) {
    
    t_col <- paste0(evidence, "_diagnostic_t")
    f_col <- paste0(evidence, "_diagnostic_f") 
    
    if(t_col %in% names(diagnostic_data) && f_col %in% names(diagnostic_data)) {
      
      # Calculate DeltaP for each participant
      test_data <- diagnostic_data %>%
        filter(!is.na(!!sym(t_col)) & !is.na(!!sym(f_col))) %>%
        mutate(delta_p = (!!sym(t_col) - !!sym(f_col)) / 100)
      
      if(nrow(test_data) > 0) {
        
        # Test if DeltaP differs by verdict (coherence effect)
        guilty_data <- test_data %>% filter(verdict == "Guilty")
        not_guilty_data <- test_data %>% filter(verdict == "Not Guilty")
        
        if(nrow(guilty_data) > 0 && nrow(not_guilty_data) > 0) {
          
          # Statistical test
          t_test_result <- t.test(guilty_data$delta_p, not_guilty_data$delta_p)
          
          coherence_results[[evidence]] <- list(
            evidence_type = evidence,
            guilty_mean_delta_p = mean(guilty_data$delta_p, na.rm = TRUE),
            not_guilty_mean_delta_p = mean(not_guilty_data$delta_p, na.rm = TRUE),
            coherence_effect = mean(guilty_data$delta_p, na.rm = TRUE) - mean(not_guilty_data$delta_p, na.rm = TRUE),
            p_value = t_test_result$p.value,
            t_statistic = as.numeric(t_test_result$statistic),
            significant = t_test_result$p.value < 0.05,
            n_guilty = nrow(guilty_data),
            n_not_guilty = nrow(not_guilty_data)
          )
        } else {
          cat("Warning: Insufficient data for", evidence, "- Guilty:", nrow(guilty_data), "Not Guilty:", nrow(not_guilty_data), "\n")
        }
      }
    } else {
      cat("Warning: Required columns not found for", evidence, "\n")
    }
  }
  
  return(coherence_results)
}

Function to combine evidence using likelihood ratios (Type 1 independent combination)

combine_independent_evidence <- function(causal_power_results, participant_data) {
  
  combined_results <- list()
  
  # Focus on diagnostic condition results
  diagnostic_results <- causal_power_results[grepl("_diagnostic", names(causal_power_results))]
  
  if(length(diagnostic_results) > 0) {
    
    # Get all participant IDs from diagnostic condition
    all_ids <- unique(unlist(lapply(diagnostic_results, function(x) x$id)))
    
    for(participant_id in all_ids) {
      
      log_likelihood_ratios <- c()
      individual_predictions <- c()
      evidence_names <- c()
      
      for(result_name in names(diagnostic_results)) {
        participant_row <- diagnostic_results[[result_name]] %>% 
          filter(id == participant_id)
        
        if(nrow(participant_row) > 0) {
          # Calculate likelihood ratio: P(E|G) / P(E|¬G)
          if(participant_row$p_e_given_ng > 0.01) { # Avoid division by zero
            lr <- participant_row$p_e_given_g / participant_row$p_e_given_ng
            log_lr <- log(lr)
            log_likelihood_ratios <- c(log_likelihood_ratios, log_lr)
            individual_predictions <- c(individual_predictions, participant_row$predicted_guilt_percentage)
            evidence_names <- c(evidence_names, result_name)
          }
        }
      }
      
      if(length(log_likelihood_ratios) > 0) {
        # Combined log likelihood ratio
        combined_log_lr <- sum(log_likelihood_ratios)
        
        # Convert back to probability (assuming equal priors)
        combined_odds <- exp(combined_log_lr)
        combined_prob <- combined_odds / (1 + combined_odds)
        
        # Get participant's actual verdict and probability rating
        participant_actual <- participant_data %>% filter(id == participant_id)
        
        if(nrow(participant_actual) > 0) {
          combined_results[[paste0("participant_", participant_id)]] <- list(
            participant_id = participant_id,
            verdict = participant_actual$verdict[1],
            actual_probability = participant_actual$probability[1],
            predicted_probability = combined_prob * 100,
            combined_log_lr = combined_log_lr,
            individual_predictions = individual_predictions,
            evidence_names = evidence_names,
            n_evidence_pieces = length(log_likelihood_ratios)
          )
        }
      }
    }
  }
  
  return(combined_results)
}

Function to calculate model fit statistics

calculate_model_fit <- function(combined_results) {
  
  if(length(combined_results) == 0) {
    return(list(rmse = NA, mae = NA, correlation = NA, r_squared = NA, n_participants = 0))
  }
  
  # Extract predictions and actual values
  predictions <- sapply(combined_results, function(x) x$predicted_probability)
  actual <- sapply(combined_results, function(x) x$actual_probability)
  
  # Remove any NA values
  valid_indices <- !is.na(predictions) & !is.na(actual) & is.finite(predictions) & is.finite(actual)
  predictions <- predictions[valid_indices]
  actual <- actual[valid_indices]
  
  if(length(predictions) > 2 && length(actual) > 2) {
    
    # Calculate fit statistics
    rmse <- sqrt(mean((predictions - actual)^2))
    mae <- mean(abs(predictions - actual))
    correlation <- cor(predictions, actual, use = "complete.obs")
    
    # R-squared
    ss_res <- sum((actual - predictions)^2)
    ss_tot <- sum((actual - mean(actual))^2)
    r_squared <- 1 - (ss_res / ss_tot)
    
    return(list(
      rmse = rmse,
      mae = mae,
      correlation = correlation,
      r_squared = r_squared,
      n_participants = length(predictions)
    ))
  } else {
    return(list(
      rmse = NA,
      mae = NA, 
      correlation = NA,
      r_squared = NA,
      n_participants = length(predictions)
    ))
  }
}

Main Analysis Function

run_type1_causal_power_analysis <- function(data_file_path) {
  
  # Read data (modify path as needed)
  data <- read.csv(data_file_path)
  names(data) <- trimws(names(data))
  
  # Evidence pieces
  evidence_cols <- c("p1", "p2", "p3", "p4", "d1", "d2", "d3", "d4")
  
  cat("=============================================================================")
  cat("TYPE 1 CAUSAL POWER MODEL ANALYSIS") 
  cat("=============================================================================")
  
  cat("Data summary:\n")
  cat("Total participants:", nrow(data), "\n")
  cat("Conditions:", paste(unique(data$condition), collapse = ", "), "\n")
  cat("Verdicts:", paste(unique(data$verdict), collapse = ", "), "\n\n")
  
  # Step 1: Apply causal power equations
  cat("Step 1: Applying causal power diagnostic equations...\n")
  causal_power_results <- apply_causal_power_equations(data, evidence_cols)
  cat("Completed causal power predictions for", length(causal_power_results), "evidence-condition combinations.\n\n")
  
  # Step 2: Test coherence effects on causal power estimates  
  cat("Step 2: Testing coherence effects on causal power estimates...\n")
  coherence_results <- test_coherence_on_causal_power(data, evidence_cols)
  
  # Print coherence results
  cat("\nCOHERENCE EFFECTS ON CAUSAL POWER (DeltaP):\n")
  cat("==========================================")
  if(length(coherence_results) > 0) {
    for(evidence in names(coherence_results)) {
      result <- coherence_results[[evidence]]
      cat(sprintf("%s: Guilty mean DeltaP = %.3f, Not Guilty mean DeltaP = %.3f\n", 
                  toupper(evidence), result$guilty_mean_delta_p, result$not_guilty_mean_delta_p))
      cat(sprintf("      Coherence effect = %.3f, t = %.3f, p = %.3f %s\n",
                  result$coherence_effect, result$t_statistic, result$p_value,
                  ifelse(result$significant, "***", "")))
      cat(sprintf("      Sample sizes: Guilty = %d, Not Guilty = %d\n\n",
                  result$n_guilty, result$n_not_guilty))
    }
  } else {
    cat("No coherence results found. Check data structure.\n\n")
  }
  
  # Step 3: Combine evidence using Type 1 independent mechanisms
  cat("Step 3: Combining evidence using independent mechanism assumption...\n")
  combined_results <- combine_independent_evidence(causal_power_results, data)
  cat("Completed evidence combination for", length(combined_results), "participants.\n\n")
  
  # Step 4: Calculate model fit
  cat("Step 4: Calculating model fit statistics...\n")
  model_fit <- calculate_model_fit(combined_results)
  
  cat("\nMODEL FIT STATISTICS:\n")
  cat("=====================\n")
  if(!is.na(model_fit$rmse)) {
    cat(sprintf("RMSE: %.2f\n", model_fit$rmse))
    cat(sprintf("MAE: %.2f\n", model_fit$mae))
    cat(sprintf("Correlation: %.3f\n", model_fit$correlation))
    cat(sprintf("R-squared: %.3f\n", model_fit$r_squared))
  } else {
    cat("Model fit could not be calculated (insufficient valid predictions)\n")
  }
  cat(sprintf("N participants: %d\n\n", model_fit$n_participants))
  
  # Step 5: Create summary data frame for further analysis
  if(length(coherence_results) > 0) {
    summary_df <- data.frame(
      evidence = names(coherence_results),
      guilty_mean_delta_p = sapply(coherence_results, function(x) x$guilty_mean_delta_p),
      not_guilty_mean_delta_p = sapply(coherence_results, function(x) x$not_guilty_mean_delta_p), 
      coherence_effect = sapply(coherence_results, function(x) x$coherence_effect),
      p_value = sapply(coherence_results, function(x) x$p_value),
      significant = sapply(coherence_results, function(x) x$significant),
      stringsAsFactors = FALSE
    )
  } else {
    summary_df <- data.frame()
  }
  
  # Return everything for further analysis
  return(list(
    causal_power_results = causal_power_results,
    coherence_results = coherence_results,
    combined_results = combined_results,
    model_fit = model_fit,
    summary_df = summary_df,
    data = data
  ))
}

Visualization Function

plot_coherence_effects <- function(analysis_results) {
  
  plots_list <- list()
  
  if(nrow(analysis_results$summary_df) > 0) {
    summary_df <- analysis_results$summary_df
    
    # Plot 1: Coherence effects by evidence type
    p1 <- ggplot(summary_df, aes(x = evidence, y = coherence_effect)) +
      geom_col(aes(fill = significant), alpha = 0.7) +
      geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed") +
      scale_fill_manual(values = c("FALSE" = "gray", "TRUE" = "red")) +
      labs(title = "Coherence Effects on Causal Power (DeltaP)",
           subtitle = "Difference in DeltaP between Guilty and Not Guilty voters",
           x = "Evidence Type",
           y = "Coherence Effect (Guilty DeltaP - Not Guilty DeltaP)",
           fill = "Significant") +
      theme_minimal() +
      theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))
    
    plots_list$coherence_plot <- p1
    print(p1)
  }
  
  # Plot 2: Actual vs Predicted guilt judgments
  if(length(analysis_results$combined_results) > 0) {
    
    prediction_df <- data.frame(
      predicted = sapply(analysis_results$combined_results, function(x) x$predicted_probability),
      actual = sapply(analysis_results$combined_results, function(x) x$actual_probability),
      verdict = sapply(analysis_results$combined_results, function(x) x$verdict)
    )
    
    # Remove any invalid values
    prediction_df <- prediction_df %>%
      filter(!is.na(predicted) & !is.na(actual) & is.finite(predicted) & is.finite(actual))
    
    if(nrow(prediction_df) > 0) {
      p2 <- ggplot(prediction_df, aes(x = predicted, y = actual)) +
        geom_point(aes(color = verdict), alpha = 0.6) +
        geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = TRUE, color = "black") +
        geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1, linetype = "dashed", alpha = 0.5) +
        scale_color_manual(values = c("Guilty" = "red", "Not Guilty" = "blue")) +
        labs(title = "Causal Power Model: Predicted vs Actual Guilt Judgments",
             x = "Predicted Probability of Guilt (%)",
             y = "Actual Probability of Guilt (%)",
             color = "Verdict") +
        theme_minimal() +
        coord_fixed()
      
      plots_list$prediction_plot <- p2
      print(p2)
    }
  }
  
  return(plots_list)
}
